OL,6,FThat is partly because he isn't
OL,7,Fshouting about some of them because he
OL,8,Fdoesn't think they are universally
OL,9,Fpopular - such as giving more power to
OL,10,Ftrade unions - and it is partly
OL,11,Fbecause they are either practical but
OL,12,Fnot visionary (such as cash from VAT
OL,13,Fon school fees channeled to a range of
OL,14,Fpublic services) or remain vague (how
OL,15,Fexactly to build 1.5 million homes for
OL,16,Fexample).JIt is possible that he and
OL,17,Fhis advisers are spot on that the
OL,18,Fcountry simply wants the Tories out
OL,19,Fafter 14 years, and all he has to do
OL,20,Fis reassure that a Labour government
OL,21,Fwould flip-flop less and be more
OL,22,Fcompetent than them.JHere are the
OL,23,Frisks. First, if voters believe
OL,24,FSunak's and Hunt's jibes are setting
OL,25,FLabour's agenda, some of them may not
OL,26,Fthink it's worth voting for a change
